   "etag": "\"5NTCbsXue5u92XtxuV0QeM_x9B4/ltBAnaENY-hFMYLMyMNx18BtuuQ\"",
   "title": "Quoting +Rob Pike: I am the person (or at least one of the people) who proposed to the ANSI C sta...",
   "published": "2012-09-26T22:12:46.000Z",
   "updated": "2012-09-26T22:12:46.927Z",
   "id": "z13ysb1jwve1dbnev22ld1jolnn5cjx2m",
   "url": "https://plus.google.com/116810148281701144465/posts/GKfM9zWMXYp",
   "actor": {
    "id": "116810148281701144465",
    "displayName": "Russ Cox",
    "name": {
     "familyName": "Cox",
     "givenName": "Russ"
    },
    "url": "https://plus.google.com/116810148281701144465",
    "image": {
     "url": "https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-pujw2EWQuvw/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAAA/_iIJW42AXCA/photo.jpg?sz=50"
    }
   },
   "verb": "post",
   "object": {
    "objectType": "note",
    "content": "Quoting \u003cspan class=\"proflinkWrapper\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"proflinkPrefix\"\u003e+\u003c/span\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://plus.google.com/101960720994009339267\" class=\"proflink\" oid=\"101960720994009339267\"\u003eRob Pike\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/span\u003e:\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eI am the person (or at least one of the people) who proposed to the ANSI C standards committee to make memcpy work right in the case of overlap. Even though we got memmove instead, it&#39;s at least possible to use memmove everywhere and know your program won&#39;t break. I haven&#39;t used memcpy since.\u003cbr /\u003e...\u003cbr /\u003eP.S. I also proposed making malloc(0) perfectly fine, since zero is a perfectly fine value. I also, in the same letter, proposed making zero-sized arrays legal, mostly so you could do the extend-the-struct trick for a variable-sized array as the last field of the struct. I got two letters back as answer to my one. #1: Malloc(0) shouldn&#39;t work because zero-sized arrays don&#39;t work. #2: Zero-sized arrays shouldn&#39;t work because malloc(0) doesn&#39;t work. Well played, ANSI C committee, and may your lives be a living hell.\u003cbr /\u003eP.P.S. Once ANSI C came out, memmove was required to work but memcpy wasn&#39;t, so we just used memmove everywhere (and so should you). We noticed though that some of our code was extremely slow when compiled on IRIX. We dug in, and found that, rather than using an if statement to solve the overlap problem, the implementers of memmove fixed the problem by implementing memmove with a correct but remarkable technique, regardless of actual overlap: 1. malloc a buffer. 2. memcpy source to buffer. 3. memcpy buffer to destination. 4 free buffer. The best-laid plans and all that.",
