   "etag": "\"5NTCbsXue5u92XtxuV0QeM_x9B4/k1nWf6SgZWBKJ0jDsbSPkEoK2YQ\"",
   "title": "On a Mac (or using LLVM), \"illegal instruction\" really means \"the C compiler knew that you used a...",
   "published": "2012-05-17T14:05:56.000Z",
   "updated": "2012-05-17T14:05:56.566Z",
   "id": "z133hhliztnxfnbsd22ld1jolnn5cjx2m",
   "url": "https://plus.google.com/116810148281701144465/posts/2YhKN3ibTYy",
   "actor": {
    "id": "116810148281701144465",
    "displayName": "Russ Cox",
    "name": {
     "familyName": "Cox",
     "givenName": "Russ"
    },
    "url": "https://plus.google.com/116810148281701144465",
    "image": {
     "url": "https://lh4.googleusercontent.com/-pujw2EWQuvw/AAAAAAAAAAI/AAAAAAAAAAA/_iIJW42AXCA/photo.jpg?sz=50"
    }
   },
   "verb": "post",
   "object": {
    "objectType": "note",
    "content": "On a Mac (or using LLVM), &quot;illegal instruction&quot; really means &quot;the C compiler knew that you used a pointer without initializing it, but instead of telling you so that you could fix your program, it emitted a guaranteed run-time fault&quot;. \u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e$ cat x.c\u003cbr /\u003eint main() { char *p; return *p; }\u003cbr /\u003e$ gcc -Wall -Werror -O2 x.c\u003cbr /\u003e$ ./a.out\u003cbr /\u003eIllegal instruction: 4 (core dumped)\u003cbr /\u003e$ gcc -v 2&gt;&amp;1 | tail -1\u003cbr /\u003egcc version 4.2.1 (Based on Apple Inc. build 5658) (LLVM build 2336.1.00)\u003cbr /\u003e$ gcc -Wall -Werror -S -O2 x.c\u003cbr /\u003e$ cat x.s\u003cbr /\u003e...\u003cbr /\u003e_main:\u003cbr /\u003epushq\t%rbp\u003cbr /\u003emovq\t%rsp, %rbp\u003cbr /\u003eud2\u003cbr /\u003e...\u003cbr /\u003e$\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003eThe LLVM blog says that emitting warnings is &quot;really hard&quot; [1], and maybe it is, but you know what? It&#39;s also part of your job as a compiler writer. It is inexcusable, when warnings have been requested, to emit a guaranteed trap instruction in a program instead of telling the programmer something is wrong.\u003cbr /\u003e\u003cbr /\u003e[1] \u003ca href=\"http://blog.llvm.org/2011/05/what-every-c-programmer-should-know_21.html\" \u003ehttp://blog.llvm.org/2011/05/what-every-c-programmer-should-know_21.html\u003c/a\u003e",
    "originalContent": "",
    "url": "https://plus.google.com/116810148281701144465/posts/2YhKN3ibTYy",
    "replies": {
     "totalItems": 5,
     "selfLink": "https://www.googleapis.com/plus/v1/activities/z133hhliztnxfnbsd22ld1jolnn5cjx2m/comments"
    },
